WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.630 --> 00:00:04.020
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:04.020 --> 00:00:07.440
This is a free, complete course for the CCNA.

00:00:07.440 --> 00:00:11.360
If you like these videos, please subscribe
to follow along with the series.

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:16.170
Also, please like and leave a comment, and
share the video to help spread this free series

00:00:16.170 --> 00:00:17.240
of videos.

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:19.009
Thanks for your help.

00:00:19.009 --> 00:00:23.369
In this video we’ll take a look at the fundamentals
of wireless networks.

00:00:23.369 --> 00:00:31.619
The exam topics we will cover are 1.1.d, access
points, 1.11.a, nonoverlapping wi-fi channels,

00:00:31.619 --> 00:00:36.140
1.11.b, SSID, and 1.11.c, RF.

00:00:36.140 --> 00:00:40.830
We will cover these and other wireless exam
topics in greater depth in future videos,

00:00:40.830 --> 00:00:45.300
but this video will be a general overview
and introduction to wireless networks.

00:00:45.300 --> 00:00:48.480
Here’s what we’ll cover in this video.

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:51.870
I’ll introduce radio frequency, RF.

00:00:51.870 --> 00:00:58.170
RF is a range of electromagnetic wave frequencies
which have been assigned for various purposes,

00:00:58.170 --> 00:01:03.360
including AM and FM radio, microwaves, radar,
and Wi-Fi.

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:08.150
The last one is of most interest to us, of
course, because wireless LANs use Wi-Fi.

00:01:08.150 --> 00:01:14.689
I’ll talk about Wi-Fi standards as defined
in IEEE 802.11.

00:01:14.689 --> 00:01:20.929
Just like various Ethernet standards are defined
in IEEE 802.3, various wireless LAN standards

00:01:20.929 --> 00:01:23.979
are defined in IEEE 802.11.

00:01:23.979 --> 00:01:30.100
We’ll look at some fundamentals of wireless
LANs and how they differ from wired LANs.

00:01:30.100 --> 00:01:34.990
We’re going to cover a lot of new concepts
in this video, so I highly recommend taking

00:01:34.990 --> 00:01:37.080
notes as you watch.

00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:40.920
When learning new concepts taking notes is
important to help you keep the new information

00:01:40.920 --> 00:01:43.270
organized without feeling overwhelmed.

00:01:43.270 --> 00:01:48.820
Make sure to watch until the end of the video
for a bonus practice question from Boson Software’s

00:01:48.820 --> 00:01:54.939
ExSim for CCNA, my recommended practice exams
for the CCNA.

00:01:54.939 --> 00:01:59.639
First let me introduce wireless networks,
specifically wireless LANs.

00:01:59.639 --> 00:02:03.789
Although we will briefly look at other types
of wireless networks, in this section of the

00:02:03.789 --> 00:02:08.110
course we will be focusing on wireless LANs
using Wi-Fi, because that’s what you need

00:02:08.110 --> 00:02:10.980
to know for the CCNA.

00:02:10.980 --> 00:02:17.020
The standards we use for wireless LANs are
defined in IEEE 802.11, just like how wired

00:02:17.020 --> 00:02:21.400
Ethernet LANs are defined in IEEE 802.3.

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:25.900
Note that the term Wi-Fi is a trademark of
the Wi-Fi alliance, which is not directly

00:02:25.900 --> 00:02:28.700
connected to the IEEE.

00:02:28.700 --> 00:02:35.470
The Wi-Fi Alliance tests and certifies equipment
for 802.11 standards compliance and interoperability

00:02:35.470 --> 00:02:37.170
with other devices.

00:02:37.170 --> 00:02:43.470
Devices which have been Wi-Fi certified can
use the Wi-Fi certified mark like this.

00:02:43.470 --> 00:02:47.980
For example, this is a photo of the back side
of one of the Cisco wireless access points

00:02:47.980 --> 00:02:50.980
that I will be using to make these videos.

00:02:50.980 --> 00:02:54.110
As you can see, it has been certified by the
Wi-Fi alliance.

00:02:54.110 --> 00:03:00.820
So, although the Wi-Fi alliance certifies
devices for compliance with the 802.11 standards,

00:03:00.820 --> 00:03:06.070
Wi-Fi isn’t technically the correct term
to refer to 802.11 wireless LANs.

00:03:06.070 --> 00:03:11.620
However, Wi-Fi has become the common term
that people use to refer to 802.11 wireless

00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:16.480
LANs and I will use both terms throughout
these videos.

00:03:16.480 --> 00:03:19.760
Wireless networks have some issues that we
need to deal with.

00:03:19.760 --> 00:03:25.260
First of all, all devices within range receive
all frames, like devices connected to an Ethernet

00:03:25.260 --> 00:03:26.720
hub.

00:03:26.720 --> 00:03:31.120
When using an Ethernet switch, the switch
is able to forward frames only to the intended

00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:32.510
recipient.

00:03:32.510 --> 00:03:38.400
In addition, switches allow devices to function
using full-duplex, so devices can both send

00:03:38.400 --> 00:03:43.340
and receive frames at the same time and collisions
shouldn’t occur unless there is some problem

00:03:43.340 --> 00:03:45.610
in the network.

00:03:45.610 --> 00:03:50.630
However when using an ethernet hub, the hub
will always flood all frames it receives,

00:03:50.630 --> 00:03:54.760
and collisions can occur when multiple devices
try to send and receive traffic at the same

00:03:54.760 --> 00:03:56.980
time.

00:03:56.980 --> 00:04:02.410
Like devices connected to an Ethernet hub,
when a wireless device transmits a frame all

00:04:02.410 --> 00:04:07.310
wireless-enabled devices within range will
be able to pick up that frame.

00:04:07.310 --> 00:04:12.819
The signal isn’t contained within a physical
wire, because the signal consists of electromagnetic

00:04:12.819 --> 00:04:15.870
waves radiating out from the transmitting
device.

00:04:15.870 --> 00:04:21.060
This can lead to data privacy concerns, as
well as collisions when devices communicate

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:23.770
on the same channel at the same time.

00:04:23.770 --> 00:04:29.560
So, because all devices within range receive
the frames, privacy of data within the LAN

00:04:29.560 --> 00:04:31.430
is a greater concern.

00:04:31.430 --> 00:04:36.030
In wired networks we don’t usually encrypt
data within the LAN, only when sending data

00:04:36.030 --> 00:04:38.830
over a shared network such as the Internet.

00:04:38.830 --> 00:04:43.270
However, for wireless networks it is very
important to encrypt data even within the

00:04:43.270 --> 00:04:48.760
LAN, or else anyone with a device in range
of the transmitter can access that data.

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:56.740
Also, to avoid collisions and facilitate half-duplex
communications, CSMA/CA, carrier sense multiple

00:04:56.740 --> 00:04:59.690
access with collision avoidance, is used.

00:04:59.690 --> 00:05:04.230
That’s similar to another term I mentioned
earlier in the course.

00:05:04.230 --> 00:05:10.669
CSMA/CD is used in wired networks to detect
and recover from collisions.

00:05:10.669 --> 00:05:16.280
CSMA/CA is used in wireless networks to avoid
collisions before they occur.

00:05:16.280 --> 00:05:22.770
Basically, when using CSMA/CA a device will
wait for other devices to stop transmitting

00:05:22.770 --> 00:05:25.010
before it transmits data itself.

00:05:25.010 --> 00:05:28.910
Let’s look at a simple flowchart of the
process.

00:05:28.910 --> 00:05:33.380
The transmitting device assembles the frame,
prepares it to be sent.

00:05:33.380 --> 00:05:35.850
Then it listens to check if the channel is
free.

00:05:35.850 --> 00:05:41.160
If the channel is not free, it will wait for
a random period of time.

00:05:41.160 --> 00:05:43.080
Then it will listen again.

00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:46.930
If the channel is free this time, it will
transmit the frame.

00:05:46.930 --> 00:05:51.430
Note that this is a simplification of the
process, and there is an optional feature

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:57.740
in which the transmitting device sends a ‘request
to send’, RTS, packet and waits for a ‘clear

00:05:57.740 --> 00:06:03.440
to send’, CTS, packet from the receiver
before actually sending the data packet.

00:06:03.440 --> 00:06:08.160
But this is just extra information, not something
you need to know for the CCNA.

00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:13.230
But make sure you know the term CSMA/CA and
that it is used in wireless LANs to avoid

00:06:13.230 --> 00:06:16.000
collisions.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.500
Another issue that we must deal with is that
wireless communications are regulated by various

00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:23.280
international and national bodies.

00:06:23.280 --> 00:06:27.290
You aren’t allowed to transmit data on any
channel you want, and which channels you are

00:06:27.290 --> 00:06:30.449
allowed to use can vary depending on the country.

00:06:30.449 --> 00:06:36.590
Fortunately, the 802.11 standard outlines
which frequencies can be used for wireless

00:06:36.590 --> 00:06:40.540
LANs, and devices are designed to use those
frequencies.

00:06:40.540 --> 00:06:44.870
We also must consider the wireless signal
coverage area.

00:06:44.870 --> 00:06:50.370
In wired connections we do have to consider
the cable length and in some cases electromagnetic

00:06:50.370 --> 00:06:56.540
interference, but with wireless connections
there are other factors we must consider.

00:06:56.540 --> 00:07:01.210
First of all, the signal range, how far the
signal can actually travel.

00:07:01.210 --> 00:07:05.770
And there are several factors that effect
how far a signal can travel intact.

00:07:05.770 --> 00:07:11.400
Absorption, reflection, refraction, diffraction,
and scattering.

00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:13.990
Let’s briefly look at each of them.

00:07:13.990 --> 00:07:19.370
Absorption happens when a wireless signal
passes through a material and is converted

00:07:19.370 --> 00:07:22.389
into heat, weakening the original signal.

00:07:22.389 --> 00:07:24.680
Here’s an example.

00:07:24.680 --> 00:07:30.120
By the way, I took this screenshot from EMANIM,
which can be used to animate electromagnetic

00:07:30.120 --> 00:07:31.350
waves.

00:07:31.350 --> 00:07:34.900
Check out the link I put below the image to
use EMANIM, it’s free.

00:07:34.900 --> 00:07:40.169
So, a wireless access point sends a signal,
but the receiving laptop is on the other side

00:07:40.169 --> 00:07:41.490
of a wall.

00:07:41.490 --> 00:07:46.070
The wall absorbs some of the signal, resulting
in a weaker signal by the time it reaches

00:07:46.070 --> 00:07:47.280
the laptop.

00:07:47.280 --> 00:07:49.199
That’s absorption.

00:07:49.199 --> 00:07:54.930
Reflection happens when a signal bounces off
of a material, for example metal.

00:07:54.930 --> 00:07:59.630
This is why Wi-Fi reception is usually poor
in elevators, because the signal bounces off

00:07:59.630 --> 00:08:03.940
the metal and very little penetrates into
the elevator.

00:08:03.940 --> 00:08:09.060
For example if there is a metal wall between
an AP and a laptop, most likely the laptop

00:08:09.060 --> 00:08:13.360
will not receive a good signal from the AP
because much of the signal will bounce off

00:08:13.360 --> 00:08:14.800
of the wall.

00:08:14.800 --> 00:08:20.050
Refraction happens when a wave is bent when
entering a medium where the signal travels

00:08:20.050 --> 00:08:21.990
at a different speed.

00:08:21.990 --> 00:08:25.830
For example, glass and water can refract waves.

00:08:25.830 --> 00:08:28.850
Try putting a straw into a clear glass of
water.

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:31.150
It will appear as if the straw is bent.

00:08:31.150 --> 00:08:36.580
That’s because the light waves travel at
a different speed in water than in air.

00:08:36.580 --> 00:08:39.450
That’s refraction.

00:08:39.450 --> 00:08:44.480
Diffraction happens when a wave encounters
an obstacle and travels around it.

00:08:44.480 --> 00:08:48.060
This can result in blind spots behind the
obstacle.

00:08:48.060 --> 00:08:53.430
For example, this PC is blocked by some object,
and the signals from the wireless access point

00:08:53.430 --> 00:08:58.330
travel around the object to some degree, but
the PC is in a blind spot and doesn’t receive

00:08:58.330 --> 00:09:01.290
sufficient signal from the access point.

00:09:01.290 --> 00:09:03.670
That’s diffraction.

00:09:03.670 --> 00:09:07.660
Scattering happens when a material causes
a signal to scatter in all directions.

00:09:07.660 --> 00:09:13.100
Dust, smog, uneven surfaces, etc can cause
scattering.

00:09:13.100 --> 00:09:17.570
Forgive the unprofessional diagram again,
but when a signal from this wireless access

00:09:17.570 --> 00:09:22.240
point strikes this uneven surface, the signal
is scattered in all directions.

00:09:22.240 --> 00:09:24.540
That’s scattering.

00:09:24.540 --> 00:09:29.950
All of those, absorption, reflection, refraction,
diffraction, and scattering, can affect the

00:09:29.950 --> 00:09:32.820
quality of a wireless signal.

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:36.930
When planning the positioning of wireless
access points for a network, you have to take

00:09:36.930 --> 00:09:39.460
all of these into account.

00:09:39.460 --> 00:09:42.190
One more issue I want to mention is interference.

00:09:42.190 --> 00:09:46.700
Other devices using the same channels can
cause interference.

00:09:46.700 --> 00:09:50.300
For example, a wireless LAN in your neighbor’s
house or apartment.

00:09:50.300 --> 00:09:55.310
So, I think you can see that there are various
things we have to take into concern when building

00:09:55.310 --> 00:09:59.560
a wireless network that we don’t have to
think about with wired networks.

00:09:59.560 --> 00:10:06.460
Now let’s talk about radio frequency, and
electromagnetic waves in general.

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:11.920
To send wireless signals, the sender applies
an alternating current to an antenna.

00:10:11.920 --> 00:10:17.180
This creates electromagnetic fields which
propagate out as waves.

00:10:17.180 --> 00:10:23.330
Electromagnetic waves can be measured in multiple
ways, for example amplitude and frequency.

00:10:23.330 --> 00:10:27.010
Amplitude is the maximum strength of the electric
and magnetic fields.

00:10:27.010 --> 00:10:29.380
For example, look at these two waves.

00:10:29.380 --> 00:10:34.540
The red one has a higher amplitude, and the
blue one has a lower amplitude.

00:10:34.540 --> 00:10:38.490
Although these two waves have different amplitudes,
they have the same frequency, which is the

00:10:38.490 --> 00:10:41.500
next term we’ll look at.

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:45.810
Frequency measures the number of up/down cycles
per a given unit of time.

00:10:45.810 --> 00:10:48.589
the most common measurement of frequency is
hertz.

00:10:48.589 --> 00:10:51.750
Hertz is simply the number of cycles per second.

00:10:51.750 --> 00:10:56.070
Then of course there are kilohertz, thousands
of cycles per second.

00:10:56.070 --> 00:10:59.360
Megahertz, millions of cycles per second.

00:10:59.360 --> 00:11:02.490
Gigahertz, billions of cycles per second.

00:11:02.490 --> 00:11:05.750
And terahertz, trillions of cycles per second.

00:11:05.750 --> 00:11:08.980
Of course there are more, but these are the
common ones.

00:11:08.980 --> 00:11:10.990
Look at these two waves.

00:11:10.990 --> 00:11:15.620
Although they both have the same amplitude
this time, the red one has a higher frequency

00:11:15.620 --> 00:11:18.290
and the blue one has a lower frequency.

00:11:18.290 --> 00:11:22.620
The red one goes through more cycles per second
than the blue one.

00:11:22.620 --> 00:11:23.620
Look at this wave.

00:11:23.620 --> 00:11:26.290
Let’s say this represents one second.

00:11:26.290 --> 00:11:28.540
What is the frequency of this wave?

00:11:28.540 --> 00:11:31.020
Well, this is one cycle.

00:11:31.020 --> 00:11:32.400
This is a second cycle.

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:34.020
A third cycle.

00:11:34.020 --> 00:11:35.150
And a fourth cycle.

00:11:35.150 --> 00:11:39.450
So, this is 4 cycles per second, 4 hertz.

00:11:39.450 --> 00:11:44.270
By the way, another important term is period,
the amount of time of one cycle.

00:11:44.270 --> 00:11:51.420
So, if the frequency is 4 Hz, the period is
0.25 seconds, one quarter of one second, because

00:11:51.420 --> 00:11:54.760
4 cycles occur in one second.

00:11:54.760 --> 00:12:01.010
The visible frequency range is from about
400 THz to 790 THz.

00:12:01.010 --> 00:12:07.040
But the range we’re concerned with, radio
frequency, is from about 30 Hz to 300 GHz,

00:12:07.040 --> 00:12:09.870
and it’s used for many purposes.

00:12:09.870 --> 00:12:13.950
Actually we’re only concerned with a couple
small bands of this range.

00:12:13.950 --> 00:12:17.980
Thanks to Wikipedia for this chart of the
radio frequency spectrum.

00:12:17.980 --> 00:12:21.810
The text is a bit small so it might be hard
to read, but that’s okay.

00:12:21.810 --> 00:12:25.790
I just want to point out the two ranges used
for wireless LANs.

00:12:25.790 --> 00:12:33.000
IEEE 802.11 wireless LANs use a few sections
of the ‘ultra high frequency’ and ‘super

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:35.750
high frequency’ ranges.

00:12:35.750 --> 00:12:39.330
Wi-Fi uses two main bands, meaning frequency
ranges.

00:12:39.330 --> 00:12:42.540
First is called the 2.4 GHz band.

00:12:42.540 --> 00:12:50.560
The name is 2.4 GHz, but the actual range
is from 2.4 GHz to 2.4835 GHz.

00:12:50.560 --> 00:12:53.110
Then there is the 5 GHz band.

00:12:53.110 --> 00:12:59.420
This time the actual range is from 5.150 GHz
to 5.825 GHz.

00:12:59.420 --> 00:13:02.950
But it’s further divided into four smaller
bands.

00:13:02.950 --> 00:13:06.760
Note that you don’t have to memorize any
of these band ranges, just remember the two

00:13:06.760 --> 00:13:08.100
main ones.

00:13:08.100 --> 00:13:11.950
2.4 GHz and 5 GHz.

00:13:11.950 --> 00:13:16.430
If you want to become a wireless network expert
you might want to remember the exact ranges

00:13:16.430 --> 00:13:20.080
and bands, but for the CCNA that’s not necessary.

00:13:20.080 --> 00:13:26.710
The 2.4 GHz band typically provides further
reach in open space and better penetration

00:13:26.710 --> 00:13:28.890
of obstacles such as walls.

00:13:28.890 --> 00:13:34.980
However, more devices tend to use the 2.4
GHz band so interference can be a bigger problem

00:13:34.980 --> 00:13:37.589
compared to the 5 GHz band.

00:13:37.589 --> 00:13:43.800
Modern devices typically support both, and
it’s up to you which you want to use.

00:13:43.800 --> 00:13:50.020
Note that Wi-Fi 6, which is IEEE standard
802.11ax, has expanded the spectrum range

00:13:50.020 --> 00:13:53.130
to include a band in the 6 GHz range.

00:13:53.130 --> 00:13:58.390
I’m not sure if you’ll be asked about
the 6 GHz range in the CCNA exam, but I’m

00:13:58.390 --> 00:14:00.500
mentioning it just in case.

00:14:00.500 --> 00:14:06.600
Now, each band is divided up into multiple
channels, and devices are configured to transmit

00:14:06.600 --> 00:14:09.640
and receive traffic on one or more of these
channels.

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:14.529
I say ‘or more’ because something called
‘channel bonding’ can be used to combine

00:14:14.529 --> 00:14:19.540
channels together, but I don’t think you
need to know that for the CCNA.

00:14:19.540 --> 00:14:26.970
For example, the 2.4 GHz band is divided into
several channels, each with a 22 MHz range.

00:14:26.970 --> 00:14:29.960
Here are the channels, and note that it differs
by country.

00:14:29.960 --> 00:14:34.029
Thanks to wikipedia for the chart again, by
the way.

00:14:34.029 --> 00:14:40.850
Note that the ‘11b only’ here for channel
14 in Japan refers to 802.11b, which is an

00:14:40.850 --> 00:14:43.850
old and slow standard not used much any more.

00:14:43.850 --> 00:14:48.970
Now, an important aspect of these channels
is that they overlap.

00:14:48.970 --> 00:14:56.370
For example, channel 1 is from 2401 MHz to
2423 MHz, which has some overlap with channels

00:14:56.370 --> 00:14:58.950
2, 3, 4, and 5.

00:14:58.950 --> 00:15:03.910
To avoid interference between adjacent wireless
access points, we have to carefully choose

00:15:03.910 --> 00:15:08.880
which channels we configure our access points
to use.

00:15:08.880 --> 00:15:13.550
In a small wireless LAN with only a single
access point, you can use any channel, because

00:15:13.550 --> 00:15:16.880
there are no other access points that can
cause interference.

00:15:16.880 --> 00:15:22.760
However, in larger wireless LANs with multiple
APs, it’s important that adjacent APs don’t

00:15:22.760 --> 00:15:24.940
use overlapping channels.

00:15:24.940 --> 00:15:29.040
This helps avoid interference between devices
transmitting on the same channel.

00:15:29.040 --> 00:15:33.980
If overlapping channels are used, it will
result in reduced performance and a worse

00:15:33.980 --> 00:15:36.540
user experience.

00:15:36.540 --> 00:15:43.640
In the 2.4 GHz band, it is recommended to
use three channels, 1, 6, and 11.

00:15:43.640 --> 00:15:47.860
Here is a diagram of the channels in the 2.4
GHz band.

00:15:47.860 --> 00:15:51.329
Notice that channels 1, 6, and 11 don’t
overlap with each other.

00:15:51.329 --> 00:15:57.470
So, we can have an AP using channel 1, an
AP using channel 6, and an AP using channel

00:15:57.470 --> 00:16:00.890
11 and they won’t interfere with each other.

00:16:00.890 --> 00:16:05.581
Note that outside of north america you can
use other combinations, but for the CCNA you

00:16:05.581 --> 00:16:10.079
should really remember the 1, 6, and 11 combination.

00:16:10.079 --> 00:16:15.790
And as for the 5 GHz band, it consists of
non-overlapping channels, so it is much easier

00:16:15.790 --> 00:16:21.450
to avoid interference between adjacent wireless
access points.

00:16:21.450 --> 00:16:26.750
Using those three channels in the 2.4 GHz
band, you can place APs in a ‘honeycomb’

00:16:26.750 --> 00:16:31.959
pattern to provide complete coverage of an
area without interference between channels.

00:16:31.959 --> 00:16:36.829
The diagram on the left shows how you can
do that with channels 1, 6, and 11, as well

00:16:36.829 --> 00:16:39.930
as other patterns for those outside of north
america.

00:16:39.930 --> 00:16:44.850
Here’s a large version of the 1-6-11 honeycomb
pattern.

00:16:44.850 --> 00:16:49.990
Note that the coverage area of each AP overlaps
to provide complete coverage of the area,

00:16:49.990 --> 00:16:54.110
but the frequencies don’t overlap, which
helps avoid interference between the access

00:16:54.110 --> 00:16:55.440
points.

00:16:55.440 --> 00:16:59.339
When you have to provide wireless coverage
over a large space, you should arrange your

00:16:59.339 --> 00:17:03.240
access points like this.

00:17:03.240 --> 00:17:08.860
Just like there have been various 802.3 Ethernet
standards, there are plenty of 802.11 Wi-Fi

00:17:08.860 --> 00:17:14.459
standards too that use different frequencies
and provide different data rates.

00:17:14.459 --> 00:17:21.860
Starting with the original 802.11 which was
released in 1997 all the way to 802.11ax,

00:17:21.860 --> 00:17:27.280
also known as Wi-Fi 6, which was released
in 2019, here are the 802.11 standards you

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:28.280
should know.

00:17:28.280 --> 00:17:33.690
I know it’s a lot of work, but I do recommend
memorizing these standard names, the frequencies

00:17:33.690 --> 00:17:38.290
they use, and their maximum theoretical data
rates for the test.

00:17:38.290 --> 00:17:41.360
Note that these maximum data rates are theoretical.

00:17:41.360 --> 00:17:45.470
For many reasons you’re probably going to
get much lower data rates than the theoretical

00:17:45.470 --> 00:17:47.320
maximums.

00:17:47.320 --> 00:17:55.230
Also notice that 802.11n is known as Wi-Fi
4, ac is known as Wi-Fi 5, and ax is known

00:17:55.230 --> 00:18:00.920
as Wi-Fi 6, however there is no official Wi-Fi
1, 2, or 3.

00:18:00.920 --> 00:18:03.520
That’s all I have to say about this.

00:18:03.520 --> 00:18:07.700
Take some time to memorize these different
standards and their characteristics.

00:18:07.700 --> 00:18:11.419
Of course, I recommend using the flashcards
to help you do that.

00:18:11.419 --> 00:18:17.290
By the way, 802.11-enabled devices might support
one of these standards, some of them, or all

00:18:17.290 --> 00:18:18.290
of them.

00:18:18.290 --> 00:18:22.600
So, I recommend checking which standards are
supported before you buy a device.

00:18:22.600 --> 00:18:27.610
Also, for some homework try looking up the
WiFi standards supported by the wireless devices

00:18:27.610 --> 00:18:29.230
you own.

00:18:29.230 --> 00:18:33.640
For example, if you have an iPhone you can
check Apple’s website to see which standards

00:18:33.640 --> 00:18:34.640
it supports.

00:18:34.640 --> 00:18:37.760
Here’s an example for the iPhone 10.

00:18:37.760 --> 00:18:44.160
It supports 802.11 A, B, G, N, and AC.

00:18:44.160 --> 00:18:49.740
Finally let’s look at another important
part of 802.11, service sets.

00:18:49.740 --> 00:18:54.970
802.11 defines different kinds of service
sets which are groups of wireless network

00:18:54.970 --> 00:18:56.299
devices.

00:18:56.299 --> 00:19:02.250
There are three main types, independent service
sets, infrastructure service sets, and mesh

00:19:02.250 --> 00:19:04.210
service sets.

00:19:04.210 --> 00:19:09.580
All devices in a service set share the same
SSID, service set ID.

00:19:09.580 --> 00:19:11.570
You might have heard that term before.

00:19:11.570 --> 00:19:16.620
The SSID is a human-readable name which identifies
the service set.

00:19:16.620 --> 00:19:21.480
And it does not have to be unique, although
it’s best to configure unique SSIDs since

00:19:21.480 --> 00:19:26.020
that’s what you’ll be looking at when
you select which network to connect to.

00:19:26.020 --> 00:19:30.400
Here are the SSIDs my phone can detect as
I sit here at my desk.

00:19:30.400 --> 00:19:35.510
Now, I said SSIDs are human-readable, meaning
they can be given easy-to-read names like

00:19:35.510 --> 00:19:38.660
‘Jeremy’s Wi-Fi’ or something like that.

00:19:38.660 --> 00:19:42.410
In this case, these names aren’t exactly
the most easily readable.

00:19:42.410 --> 00:19:47.190
However, I could easily change the SSID of
my wireless LAN to something simpler.

00:19:47.190 --> 00:19:51.220
Anyway, let’s look at the different types
of service sets.

00:19:51.220 --> 00:19:57.690
First, an IBSS, independent basic service
set, is a wireless network in which two or

00:19:57.690 --> 00:20:03.450
more wireless devices connect directly without
using an AP, access point.

00:20:03.450 --> 00:20:06.250
These are also called ad hoc networks.

00:20:06.250 --> 00:20:11.730
They be used, for example, for file transfer
such as when using Apple’s airdrop.

00:20:11.730 --> 00:20:16.020
However they are not scalable beyond a few
devices and are typically only used for limited

00:20:16.020 --> 00:20:20.140
purposes such as quick file transfers like
airdrop.

00:20:20.140 --> 00:20:26.610
Next, a BSS, basic service set, is a kind
of infrastructure service set in which clients

00:20:26.610 --> 00:20:32.230
connect to each other via an AP, access point,
but not directly to each other.

00:20:32.230 --> 00:20:35.049
Remember I said there are three kinds of service
sets?

00:20:35.049 --> 00:20:39.750
First is independent, which I just showed
you, and second is infrastructure.

00:20:39.750 --> 00:20:43.570
BSS is a kind of infrastructure service set.

00:20:43.570 --> 00:20:48.970
The AP serves as network infrastructure connecting
different wireless clients together.

00:20:48.970 --> 00:20:55.910
A BSSID, basic service set ID, is used to
uniquely identify the AP.

00:20:55.910 --> 00:21:00.940
Other APs can use the same SSID, which is
Jeremy’s Wi-Fi in this case, but not the

00:21:00.940 --> 00:21:03.260
same BSSID.

00:21:03.260 --> 00:21:09.350
The BSSID is the MAC address of the AP’s
radio, and as you know MAC addresses are unique.

00:21:09.350 --> 00:21:16.090
To be part of the BSS, wireless devices request
to associate with the BSS.

00:21:16.090 --> 00:21:22.010
Wireless devices that have associated with
the BSS are called clients or stations.

00:21:22.010 --> 00:21:26.130
Another important term is BSA, basic service
area.

00:21:26.130 --> 00:21:29.770
This is the area around the AP where it’s
signal is usable.

00:21:29.770 --> 00:21:33.530
What’s different between a BSS and a BSA?

00:21:33.530 --> 00:21:39.789
Well, a BSS is a group of devices which are
wirelessly connected via an AP.

00:21:39.789 --> 00:21:45.700
BSA just refers to the physical area around
the AP where devices will be able to associate

00:21:45.700 --> 00:21:48.150
with the AP and join its BSS.

00:21:48.150 --> 00:21:55.049
So, BSS is a group of devices, and BSA is
a physical area.

00:21:55.049 --> 00:22:00.120
And note that clients must communicate via
the AP, not directly with each other.

00:22:00.120 --> 00:22:04.980
The traffic must flow through the AP before
going to the other client, even if the other

00:22:04.980 --> 00:22:08.270
client is in range of the sender’s signal.

00:22:08.270 --> 00:22:14.480
To create larger wireless LANs beyond the
range of a single AP, we use an ESS, extended

00:22:14.480 --> 00:22:16.240
service set.

00:22:16.240 --> 00:22:18.950
This is the second kind of infrastructure
service set.

00:22:18.950 --> 00:22:27.250
Note how there are two BSSs, BSS1 and BSS2,
but together they form an ESS.

00:22:27.250 --> 00:22:32.350
APs with their own BSSs are connected by a
wired network.

00:22:32.350 --> 00:22:37.940
Notice how the APs for BSS1 and BSS2 are connected
by a switch.

00:22:37.940 --> 00:22:43.330
Each BSS uses the same SSID, Jeremy’s Wi-Fi
in this case.

00:22:43.330 --> 00:22:49.190
However each BSS has a unique BSSID, notice
how they are different in the diagram.

00:22:49.190 --> 00:22:54.540
Also, each BSS uses a different channel to
avoid interference.

00:22:54.540 --> 00:23:01.929
Notice that BSS1 is using 2.4 GHz channel
1, and BSS2 is using channel 6.

00:23:01.929 --> 00:23:07.220
Clients can pass between APs without having
to reconnect, providing a seamless Wi-Fi experience

00:23:07.220 --> 00:23:09.910
when moving between APs.

00:23:09.910 --> 00:23:15.450
This is called roaming, when you move between
two APs in an extended service set.

00:23:15.450 --> 00:23:20.320
Note that there should be some overlap in
the BSAs, about 10 to 15 percent, or else

00:23:20.320 --> 00:23:25.120
the connectivity can be lost when moving between
APs.

00:23:25.120 --> 00:23:30.669
The final kind of service set we’ll look
at is an MBSS, Mesh Basic Service Set.

00:23:30.669 --> 00:23:35.460
An MBSS can be used in situations where it’s
difficult to run an Ethernet connection to

00:23:35.460 --> 00:23:37.410
every AP.

00:23:37.410 --> 00:23:39.530
The mesh APs use two radios.

00:23:39.530 --> 00:23:45.450
One to provide a BSS to wireless clients so
they can connect to the network, and one radio

00:23:45.450 --> 00:23:50.710
to form the mesh network between the APs,
to form a backhaul network which bridges traffic

00:23:50.710 --> 00:23:53.100
from AP to AP.

00:23:53.100 --> 00:23:57.960
For example if this PC wants to send traffic
to the Internet, it sends traffic to its nearest

00:23:57.960 --> 00:24:03.419
AP, which then bridges the traffic from AP
to AP over the backhaul network back to the

00:24:03.419 --> 00:24:04.419
switch.

00:24:04.419 --> 00:24:10.360
At least one switch is connected to the wired
network, and it’s called the RAP, root access

00:24:10.360 --> 00:24:11.600
point.

00:24:11.600 --> 00:24:14.450
This is the RAP in this network.

00:24:14.450 --> 00:24:18.320
The other APs are called MAPs, Mesh Access
Points.

00:24:18.320 --> 00:24:23.440
A protocol is used to determine the past path
that traffic should take through the mesh,

00:24:23.440 --> 00:24:28.640
similar to how dynamic routing protocols are
used to determine the best path to a destination.

00:24:28.640 --> 00:24:32.760
Now, most wireless networks aren’t standalone
networks.

00:24:32.760 --> 00:24:38.169
Rather, they are a way for wireless clients
to connect to the wired network infrastructure,

00:24:38.169 --> 00:24:42.120
and the AP serves to translate between the
two mediums.

00:24:42.120 --> 00:24:48.840
In 802.11, the upstream wired network is called
the DS, distribution system.

00:24:48.840 --> 00:24:53.890
Each wireless BSS or ESS is mapped to a VLAN
in the wired network.

00:24:53.890 --> 00:24:55.929
Here’s an example.

00:24:55.929 --> 00:25:01.240
The SSID Jeremy’s Wi-Fi is translated to
VLAN 10 on the wired network, which is the

00:25:01.240 --> 00:25:03.539
distribution system.

00:25:03.539 --> 00:25:09.330
The wired hosts in VLAN 10 will be able to
communicate with the wireless hosts in Jeremy’s

00:25:09.330 --> 00:25:10.460
Wi-Fi.

00:25:10.460 --> 00:25:16.559
And it’s possible for an AP to provide multiple
wireless LANs, each with a unique SSID.

00:25:16.559 --> 00:25:20.940
This is the same as how a switch can divide
a single physical wired network into multiple

00:25:20.940 --> 00:25:22.480
VLANs.

00:25:22.480 --> 00:25:27.600
Each wireless LAN is mapped to a separate
VLAN and connected to the network via a trunk.

00:25:27.600 --> 00:25:29.870
Here’s an example.

00:25:29.870 --> 00:25:36.420
There are two wireless LANs with their own
SSIDs, Jeremy’s Wi-Fi and Guest Wi-Fi.

00:25:36.420 --> 00:25:41.400
Although as I said before, SSIDs don’t have
to be unique, but usually they are.

00:25:41.400 --> 00:25:47.640
Jeremy’s Wi-Fi is mapped to VLAN 10, and
Guest Wi-Fi is mapped to VLAN 11, and the

00:25:47.640 --> 00:25:52.440
AP is connected to the switch via a trunk
which allows both VLAN 10 and 11.

00:25:52.440 --> 00:25:58.309
Also, notice that each wireless LAN uses a
unique BSSID, usually by incrementing the

00:25:58.309 --> 00:26:01.150
last digit of the BSSID by one.

00:26:01.150 --> 00:26:08.800
So, the BSSID of Jeremy’s Wi-Fi ends with
3456, and the BSSID of guest Wi-Fi ends with

00:26:08.800 --> 00:26:11.830
3457.

00:26:11.830 --> 00:26:15.140
The final thing we’ll cover is a few more
modes that APs can operate in.

00:26:15.140 --> 00:26:20.929
First, an AP in repeater mode can be used
to extend the range of a BSS.

00:26:20.929 --> 00:26:23.420
Here’s an example.

00:26:23.420 --> 00:26:28.370
The repeater will simply retransmit any signal
it receives from the AP, which will extend

00:26:28.370 --> 00:26:29.370
the range of the AP’s BSS.

00:26:29.370 --> 00:26:35.940
A repeater with a single radio must operate
on the same channel as the AP, but this can

00:26:35.940 --> 00:26:40.010
drastically reduce the overall throughput
on the channel, since the repeater will be

00:26:40.010 --> 00:26:45.000
repeating the AP’s signals back to it using
the same channel, keeping the channel busy.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:48.720
This cuts the effective throughput of the
channel by 50%.

00:26:48.720 --> 00:26:55.010
A repeater with two radios fixes this weakness,
because it can receive on one channel and

00:26:55.010 --> 00:26:57.000
then retransmit on another channel.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:00.240
So, that’s how a wireless repeater works.

00:27:00.240 --> 00:27:07.520
Next, an AP operating as a workgroup bridge
operates as a wireless client of another AP,

00:27:07.520 --> 00:27:11.330
and can be used to connect wired devices to
the wireless network.

00:27:11.330 --> 00:27:17.679
In the example below, PC1 does not have wireless
capabilities and also does not have access

00:27:17.679 --> 00:27:19.820
to a wired connection to SW1.

00:27:19.820 --> 00:27:24.800
However, PC1 has a wired connection to the
workgroup bridge, which has a wireless connection

00:27:24.800 --> 00:27:26.060
to the AP.

00:27:26.060 --> 00:27:29.870
Now, there are two kinds of WGBs.

00:27:29.870 --> 00:27:36.320
Universal WGB, uWGB, is an 802.11 standard
that allows one device to be bridged to the

00:27:36.320 --> 00:27:38.230
wireless network.

00:27:38.230 --> 00:27:42.890
However what Cisco simply calls WGB is their
proprietary version which allows multiple

00:27:42.890 --> 00:27:46.000
wired clients to be bridged to the wireless
network.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:51.140
To summarize, this is a solution which allows
clients that don’t support wireless connections

00:27:51.140 --> 00:27:57.330
to connect to the wireless network via an
AP operating as a workgroup bridge.

00:27:57.330 --> 00:28:01.080
The final mode I’m going to introduce is
outdoor bridge.

00:28:01.080 --> 00:28:06.090
An outdoor bridge can be used to connect networks
over long distances without a physical cable

00:28:06.090 --> 00:28:07.669
connecting them.

00:28:07.669 --> 00:28:12.770
The APs will use specialized antennas that
focus most of the signal power in one direction,

00:28:12.770 --> 00:28:17.309
which allows the wireless connection to be
made over longer distances than normally possible.

00:28:17.309 --> 00:28:23.120
The connection can be point-to-point as in
the diagram, just two sites being connected.

00:28:23.120 --> 00:28:27.410
Or it can be point-to-multipoint, in which
multiple sites all connect to one central

00:28:27.410 --> 00:28:31.040
site, forming a hub-and-spoke topology.

00:28:31.040 --> 00:28:36.470
Okay, since we covered so many different topics
in this video let me summarize all of them

00:28:36.470 --> 00:28:38.330
with a lovely wall of text.

00:28:38.330 --> 00:28:39.790
Here it is.

00:28:39.790 --> 00:28:44.529
Now, although this summarizes the topics in
this video, make sure you know the details

00:28:44.529 --> 00:28:46.710
of each topic that we covered.

00:28:46.710 --> 00:28:50.919
If you didn’t take notes I recommend going
back in the video to take your own notes,

00:28:50.919 --> 00:28:54.880
and also using the flashcards to memorize
some of the details.

00:28:54.880 --> 00:29:00.620
Okay, in this video we covered the basics
of wireless networks, specifically wireless

00:29:00.620 --> 00:29:06.790
LANs, including radio frequency, wi-fi standards,
and wireless LAN fundamentals such as service

00:29:06.790 --> 00:29:08.130
sets.

00:29:08.130 --> 00:29:13.450
There is still a lot more to cover about wireless
networks including wireless network architectures,

00:29:13.450 --> 00:29:17.440
wireless network security, and wireless network
configuration.

00:29:17.440 --> 00:29:19.750
Those topics will be in the next few videos.

00:29:19.750 --> 00:29:25.460
As always, watch until the end of the quiz
for a bonus practice question from Boson Software’s

00:29:25.460 --> 00:29:29.440
ExSim for CCNA, the best practice exams for
the CCNA.

00:29:29.440 --> 00:29:34.390
Okay, now let’s go to quiz question 1.

00:29:34.390 --> 00:29:40.370
When using the 2.4 GHz band, which channels
should be selected when using multiple APs?

00:29:40.370 --> 00:29:44.919
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:29:44.919 --> 00:29:50.750
Okay, the answer is B, 1, 6, and 11.

00:29:50.750 --> 00:29:57.530
As this diagram shows, channels 1, 6, and
11 do not overlap, so even if APs are near

00:29:57.530 --> 00:30:00.150
each other interference can be avoided.

00:30:00.150 --> 00:30:03.169
Okay, let’s go to question 2.

00:30:03.169 --> 00:30:10.680
If an enterprise’s network is mostly wired,
what is the purpose of an AP in the network?

00:30:10.680 --> 00:30:15.170
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:30:15.170 --> 00:30:22.179
Okay, the answer is to connect wireless devices
to the wired network.

00:30:22.179 --> 00:30:28.559
In 802.11, the wired network is called the
DS, distribution system, and the AP’s main

00:30:28.559 --> 00:30:32.220
role is to connect wireless devices to the
wired network.

00:30:32.220 --> 00:30:37.039
Okay let’s go to question 3.

00:30:37.039 --> 00:30:40.360
Which of the following bands are commonly
used by wireless LANs?

00:30:40.360 --> 00:30:41.570
(select two).

00:30:41.570 --> 00:30:45.940
Pause the video now to select the best answers.

00:30:45.940 --> 00:30:53.400
Okay, the answers are A, 2.4 GHz, and D, 5
GHz.

00:30:53.400 --> 00:30:57.650
These bands are divided into channels which
are used by wireless devices to send and receive

00:30:57.650 --> 00:30:58.910
wireless signals.

00:30:58.910 --> 00:31:03.610
Okay, let’s go to question 4.

00:31:03.610 --> 00:31:08.100
Which of the following statements about an
ESS are true? (select two).

00:31:08.100 --> 00:31:12.720
Pause the video now to select the best answers.

00:31:12.720 --> 00:31:22.110
Okay, the answers are B, each BSS uses a unique
BSSID and C, roaming can provide seamless

00:31:22.110 --> 00:31:25.559
connectivity when moving between APs.

00:31:25.559 --> 00:31:32.190
A is not correct because each BSS in an ESS
should use the same SSID, and D is not correct

00:31:32.190 --> 00:31:36.370
because adjacent APs should use nonoverlapping
channels to avoid interference.

00:31:36.370 --> 00:31:42.220
Okay, let’s go to question 5.

00:31:42.220 --> 00:31:47.850
Which of the following statements is not true
about an AP that provides multiple BSSs?

00:31:47.850 --> 00:31:52.520
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:31:52.520 --> 00:32:00.049
Okay, the answer is B, each BSS shares the
same BSSID.

00:32:00.049 --> 00:32:05.210
Although it is possible for each BSS to share
the same SSID, they must have unique BSSIDs.

00:32:05.210 --> 00:32:12.120
With that said, however, it is best practice
to also use a unique SSID for each BSS.

00:32:12.120 --> 00:32:14.370
Okay, that’s all for the quiz.

00:32:14.370 --> 00:32:20.016
Now let’s try a bonus practice question
in Boson Software’s ExSim for CCNA.

